Subject: Request for a Convention of States to Address Nonviolent Marijuana Offender Incarceration and Federal Legalization

Dear Governors,

I am writing to you as a concerned citizen of the United States to propose a joint effort among states to convene a Convention of States under Article V of the U.S. Constitution. The purpose of this convention would be to discuss the urgent and overdue matter of nonviolent marijuana offender incarceration and to advance federal legalization efforts. The aim: reduce recidivism, promote economic growth, and enact restorative justice nationwide.

Let me be clear: I do not speak for any state or official. I speak as a resident, motivated by the overwhelming evidence and shifting national consensus on cannabis policy.

As of 2025, 38 states, three territories, and Washington, D.C. have legalized the medical use of cannabis—a full 76% of U.S. states. This marks a clear, data-driven movement acknowledging cannabis’s medicinal value and therapeutic potential.

For adult recreational use, 24 states, two territories, and D.C. have legalized cannabis. At least 14 more states have enacted decriminalization measures, meaning the vast majority of the U.S. now treats marijuana with greater legal leniency than federal law reflects. Of note, states such as Ohio and Minnesota have recently joined this effort, further tilting the balance toward reform.

Despite this momentum, over 31,000 people remain incarcerated in the U.S. for marijuana-related offenses—many for nonviolent crimes, disproportionately affecting communities of color. This systemic disparity not only damages individual lives but erodes faith in our justice system.

In line with Article V, two-thirds of state legislatures (34 of 50) may call a convention to propose amendments. With 76% of states already endorsing medical marijuana, the supermajority threshold has been more than met in spirit and intent—if not formally under the process yet. This moment is ripe for coordinated action.

I propose that a Convention of States be convened with the following goals:
Core Objectives

1. Reduce Recidivism
Federal legalization would help end the cycle of criminalization for nonviolent marijuana users. This would reduce caseloads for courts and lower incarceration costs.

2. Generate Tax Revenue
Legal cannabis generated over $4.2 billion in tax revenue in 2023 alone across states where it is legalized. Federal legalization could unlock billions more in revenue annually, helping to fund public education, healthcare, infrastructure, and addiction treatment.

3. Advance Social and Racial Justice
A federal mandate to review and release nonviolent cannabis offenders would correct historic injustices and begin to rebuild families torn apart by unequal enforcement.

4. Reintegrate Talent into the Economy
By expunging records and providing re-entry support, formerly incarcerated individuals could fully contribute to society—opening paths to employment, education, and housing.

5. Strengthen the U.S. Economy
According to recent estimates, the national legal cannabis market could exceed $40 billion by 2027. Reintegration of former offenders into the workforce would further boost economic productivity and tax bases.

If obtaining momentum is a concern, organizations like the Last Prisoner Project, NORML, and Cannabis Freedom Alliance have already galvanized millions in support of similar reforms. Public opinion, too, has evolved: a 2024 Gallup poll found that 72% of Americans support marijuana legalization, including a growing number of conservative and independent voters.

We are nearing a constitutional tipping point. If even three additional governors from states yet to legalize or decriminalize cannabis were to join this initiative, the two-thirds threshold for a Convention of States becomes a tangible reality. Their leadership would reflect not only the will of their constituents but also a national commitment to pragmatic, humane, and economically intelligent drug policy.

This convention would create a forum for states to lead where Congress has stalled. Governors, legal scholars, public health officials, and formerly incarcerated individuals could collaboratively draft a framework for reform that includes:

    A constitutional amendment or resolution addressing federal marijuana policy.

    A pathway for mass expungement of nonviolent marijuana records.

    A commitment to federal-state regulatory alignment.

In the spirit of the original discovery of insulin, which was sold for just one dollar in 1923 so that it could be freely accessible to all, this movement seeks to honor the principle that essential remedies, including justice, should never be hoarded for profit nor denied due to outdated policy.

Let this convention be a landmark moment where states take collective action to reflect the will of the people, promote justice, and usher in a new era of rational cannabis regulation.

Thank you for your time and leadership. I look forward to your response and to seeing your state participate in this historic opportunity.

Sincerely,
